#FUNCTIONS------------------------------------------
my_function <- function(arg){
  #doSTUFF
  arg + 1
}

#implicitly returns last object, can also use explicit return()
my_function(1)
## [1] 2
squares <- function(n){
  return(n**2)
}

squares(2)
## [1] 4
squares(4)
## [1] 16
weird_squares <- function(n){
  n <- n + 1
  print(paste("n is",n))
  return(squares(n))
}

n <- 3
n
## [1] 3
weird_squares(n)
## [1] "n is 4"
## [1] 16
n
## [1] 3
default_square <- function(n = 4){
  return(n**2)
}

#PROOF---------------------------------------
library(microbenchmark)
library(ggplot2)


#Two Ways of getting Means
applyF <- function(x){
  return(lapply(x,mean))
}
loopF <- function(x){
  l <- rep(NA,dim(x)[2])
  for (i in 1:dim(x)[2]){
    l[i] <- mean(x[,i])
  }
  return(l)
}
createF <- function(){
  a <- data.frame(d=rnorm(100000000), lab = sort(rep(1:1000,100000)))
  a$lab <- factor(a$lab)
  a <- split(a$d,a$lab)
  x <- data.frame(a)
  return(x)
}

x <- createF()
#TEST
n <- 100
applyWay <- microbenchmark(applyF(x),loopF(x),times = n)
## Warning in microbenchmark(applyF(x), loopF(x), times = n): less accurate
## nanosecond times to avoid potential integer overflows
autoplot(applyWay)  +
  stat_summary(fun.y=mean, geom="point", size=2, color="red")
